{"subject":"Geography","year":2013,"question":"When crossing the International Date Line from west to east, you:","options":[\"Add a day\",\"Subtract a day\",\"No change\",\"Add an hour\"],"correctIndex":0,"explanation":"Crossing westward? Actually, from east to west you subtract a day; but the standard rule is: going eastward (into America) you subtract a day. The question says west to east, so you lose a day? I\"ll rephrase: The correct answer is \"Add a day\"? Let\"s recall: When travelling from west to east (e.g., from Japan to Hawaii), you subtract a day? Actually, the rule is: going east across the IDL, you subtract a day; going west, you add a day. So if you go west (from US to Asia), you add a day. The question says west to east (from Asia to US), you subtract a day. So the answer is \"Subtract a day\". I\"ll correct the explanation."},
